{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1lichtenstein_ver02/data/sn83045462/0028060172A/1938032501/0423.xml":{"full_text":"WEATHER.\n<U. 8. Weather Bureau Forecast.)\nIncreasing cloudiness and warmer to\nnight, followed by showers and warmer\ntomorrow; colder Sunday; lowest tonight\nabout 46. Temperatures today\u2014Highest,\n56, at 3 p.m.; lowest, 37, at 5:30 a m.\nPull report on page A-2.\nClosing New York Markets, Page 14\nThe only evening paper\nin Washington with the\nAssociated Press News\nand Wirephoto Services.\n04*) Means Associated Press.\n86th YEAR. No. 34,296.\nWASHINGTON, D. C,, FRIDAY, MARCH 25, 1938\u2014FIFTY PAGES.\n\u00bb'S,r,mK. THREE CENTS.\nSENATE FACTIONS\nCOME TO TERMS\nCompromise Resolution to\nInclude Eight Charges\nMade by Bridges.\nWAY DECLARED CLEAR\nFOR FULL INVESTIGATION\nBankhead Says Joint Committee\nfor Quiz Appears to Be\nCertain.\nBACKGROUND\u2014\nTennessee Valley Authority, ad\nministrative agency for one of ad\nministration\u2019s greatest social and\neconomic experiments, was bitter\nly divided for weeks as Chairman\nA. E. Morgan and two colleagues\nengaged in personal feud. After\nconducting own inquiry, President\nRoosevelt this week dismissed Dr.\nA. E. Morgan and named Dr. Har\ncourt Morgan his successor in\nchairmanship.\nBULLETIN.\nThe Senate today adopted a com\npromise resolution calling for a\njoint Senate-House investigation\nof the Tennessee Valley Authority.\nThe resolution was proposed by\nMajority Leader Barkley. It in\ncluded some requests for informa\ntion on the T. V. A. advanced by\nSenators Bridges. Republican, of\nNew Hampshire and King, Demo\ncrat. of Utah, authors of a sepa\nrate investigation resolution.\nAll Senate groups seeking an in\nvestigation of the Tennessee Valley\nAuthority agreed today on a new reso\nlution providing for a Congressional\nInquiry.\nSenator Bridges. Republican, of New\nHampshire, an author of one T. V. A.\nInvestigation resolution, told reporters\nhe and Senator King, Democrat, of\nUtah, co-author, ha dagreed with Sen\nators Barkley. Democrat, of Kentucky,\nand Norris, independent, of Nebraska,\nauthors of other resolutions, on the\nform of a new proposal.\nSenator Bridges said the compromise\nresolution would include 8 of 23\ncharges which he originally lj*d made\n\u25a0gainst the T. V. A. and which Sen\nators Barkley and Norris had omitted\nfrom their proposals.\n\"The way is all dear now' for an\nInvestigation.\u201d Senator Bridges said.\nHe added that it had not been fin\nally determined whether the investi\ngation should be made by both the\nHouse and Senate or by the Senate\nalone, but that in either event, the\ncompromise draft of the resolution\nwould stand.\nJoint Inquiry Certain.\nHouse Speaker Bankhead said it ap\npeared certain the inquiry would be\nconducted by a joint Senate-House\ncommittee.\nHe declared it should be composed\nof \u201cfair, impartial, courageous men.\"\n\"That,\u201d he said, \"is the kind of\ncommittee I'm going to appoint\u2014if I\ncan find them.\u201d\nHe hastened to add that he meant\nthe members should be men who\nhave taken no prominent stand either\nfor or against the T. V. A. program\nSpeaker Bankhead would name the\nHouse members of the committee and\nVice President Garner the Senate\nmembers.\nCommitted to Policy.\nAdministration leaders in the Sen\nate were committed to the policy of a\nJoint investigation.\nSenator Norris had backed an in\nvestigation by the Senate alone.\nThe new resolution includes specific\nInstructions for investigation of anti\nT. V. A. activities of the private power\ncompanies as well as the Bridges\nKing charges against the T. V. A.\nAlthough a long and carefully word\ned resolution, prepared by Majority\nLeader Barkley and calling for a joint\ninquiry, included Senator Norris\u2019 re\nquest that the investigation cover the\nprivate utility companies that have op\nposed the administration's power \"yard\nstick,\u2019\u2019 Senator Norris said he opposed\nit on the ground inclusion of the\nHouse in the inquiry would make it\n\"more C06tly and unwieldy.\"\nBridges Opposes Resolution.\nSenator Bridges, on the other hand,\nhad regarded the Barkley proposal as\nunacceptable because, he asserted, it\ncontained everything asked by Senator\nNorris and none of the charges made\nby himself and Senator King.\nHouse Republicans criticised Presi\ndent Roosevelt, meanwhile, for remov\ning Arthur E. Morgan from the chair\nmanship of the T. V. A. and for per\nmitting what was called a \"demoraliz\ning national scandal\u201d concerning post\nmaster appointments.\nRepresentative Hoffman, Republican,\nof Michigan said the President\u2019s ex\nplanation of his action against Chair\nman Morgan had a hollow ring.\nsMr. Roosevelt should remember, he\nmid, that \"disregard of a constitu\ntional duty imposed on an official is\ncause for impeachment.\u201d\nRepresentative Luce. Republican,\nof Mass., contended the President\u2019s\nouster of Mr. Morgan was an attempt\nto destroy the latter\u2019s reputation and\ncharacter.\nBULLETIN\nThe Senate this afternoon ap\nproved without debate or opposition\na bill requiring all taxicabs in the\nDistrict to carry liability insurance.\nThe bill, passed by the House in\nJuly, goes back to the House for\naction on some Senate amendments.\nSimilar legislation, urged by the\nPublic Utilities Commission, the\nPederation of Citizens\u2019 Associations\nand the Board of Trade, has been\nbefore Congress for eight years, but\nthis is the first time on record the\nSenate has approved such a meas- l\nI are. I\nTwo D. C. Women Split $75,000\nOn Danieli, Second in Sweeps\nJL.\nNews Is Kept from III\nMother\u2014Daughter\nin Hysterics.\nNews that $75,000 had been dropped\ninto their laps as a result of the Irish\nSweepstakes was withheld from a sick\nWashington woman today after the\n\"thrill\u201d had sent her daughter into\nhysterical sobbing.\nTheir \u201cproblem\u201d was kept from be\ncoming more complicated by the fact\nthe horse which carried their hopes\nmissed \"first money,\u201d $150,000, by a>\nbare head.\nFearful of her reaction to the\ntidings, Mrs. Emma Barry, a house\nwife living at 3223 Third street\nN.W., was not tola at the hospital\nwhere she has been confined for a\nmonth that \"her\u201d horse, Royal Danieli.\nan 18-to-l shot, had run second in\ntoday\u2019s Grand National at Aintree,\nEngland, the race which decides the\nsweepstakes winners.\nOverjoyed that she had not ac\ncepted an offer to sell half their ticket\nbefore the race, the daughter. Miss\nLucille Barry, 23, a United States\nChamber of Commerce employe, burst\ninto tears and sought refuge from\nreporters in a restroom, where for\nmore than an hour she was under\nthe care of a nurse.\nIronically, the horse that deprived\nTokio Would Help Improve\nHarbors and Build\nPipelines.\nBACKGROUND\u2014\nGovernment of President Lazaro\nCardenas in Mexico last week seized\nthe S400.000.000 foreign-owned pe\ntroleum industry in Mexico as cli\nmax to long labor war over work\ners\u2019 demands for pay increases and\nbetter working conditions. More\nthan month ago Japan was re\nported to have been seeking right\nto improve Mazatlan Harbor, on\nMexico's west coast, in return for\nan oil-well contract, but the reports\nof negotiations were officially de\nnied.\ni By the Associated Press.\nTOKIO. March 25.\u2014Through pri\nvate companies Japan is preparing to\noffer Mexico a huge oil contract for the\npurchase of nearly 500,000 barrels of\ncrude oil annually, it was learned to\nday.\nThe contract would provide for Jap\nanese technical assistance in construc\ntion of pipelines and improvement of\nharbors on Mexico's Pacific Coast.\nOfficial quarters were silent on the\nproposal, but it was authoritatively\nlearned the same companies ap\nproached the Mexican government\nmonth before the outbreak of hostili\nties in China last year. The deal was\nnot completed.\nThe pipelines would cross the Isth\nmus of Tehuantepec, with Salina Cruz\nas the probable point of loading. The\noil would have to be piped about 150\nmiles downgrade.\nSince the outbreak of Chinese hos\ntilities Japan has ceased publication\nof oil import statistics, but official fig\nures show she brought in 1.033,677.000\ngallons (about 24,600.000 barrels) of\ncrude oil in 1936.\nSince expropriation of the foreign\noil industry by President Lazaro Car\ndenas. a major problem of the Mex\nican government has been to find a\nforeign market for its Wells, a prime\nsource of revenue.\nJapan, with the third largest navy\nin the world and a large air force op\nerating in China, has limited sources\nfor fuel.\nA Japanese official informant, dis\ncussing the possibility of obtaining\nsupplies in Mexico, recently pointed\nout President Cardenas had advised\nMexican diplomats that his dispute\nwith foreign oil companies would not\ncause him to drift \"an inch\u201d from\n\"moral solidarity with the democratic\ncountries of the world.\u201d\nJapan is linked by an anti-Com\nmunist pact with Nazi Germany and\nFascist Italy.\nBond Issue Proposed.\nMEXICO, CITY, March 25 (/P).\u2014A\ndomestic bond issue to help pay for\nthe $400,000,000 expropriated Amer\nican and British oil properties was\nproposed today by Finance Minister\nEduardo Suarez.\nGovernors of 24 states at a confer\nence at which Suarez made the pro\nposal pledged financial aid for the\nsame purpose. They promised a con\ntribution of 5 per cent of their yearly\nstate budgets to w'ipe out the petro\nleum \u201cdebt.\u201d\nA financial plan to be adopted by\nthe government in indemnifying the\ncompanies for their properties will be\nmapped at a meeting of the governors\nwith the finance minister tomorrow.\nMeanwhile, voluntary subscriptions\nlor a national fund to pay the in\ndemnity grew to 78,000 pesos ($19,000).\nRICHMOND EXECUTIVE\nDIES IN 60-F00T FALL\nBody, Plunging From Viaduct,\nLands Almost at Group of\nPersons Standing Below.\nBy the Associated Press.\nRICHMOND, Va., March 25.\u2014A\nman identified by Richmond police as\nLeon C. White, vice president and\nsales manager of the Albers Co., which\nmakes extract here, fell 60 feet to his\ndeath from the Fifth street viaduct\nhere this morning.\nHis body landed almost at a group\nof colored persons who were standing\nat that point in Shockoe Valley, a\nlarge ravine which cuts through a\npart of the city.\nPolice said he was identified by tax\nreceipts in his pocket. They said he\nlived with his sister, Leila W. White,\nand his 10-year-old daughter at 3X05\nFirst avenue.\nMISS LUCILLE BARRY.\n\u2014Star Staff Photo.\nthe Washingtonians of another $75,000\nwas Battleship, owned by Mrs. Marion\ndu Pont Somerville Scott of nearby\nVirginia. A former winner on the\nMaryland tracks, he was the first\nAmerican-bred, American-owned horse\never to win the Grand National.\ni See RACE, Page A-3.)\nWOULOSUITA. F. L\nGreen Willing to Swap That\nMinimum for Mandatory\nAnnual Increase.\nBy she Associated Press.\nWilliam Green told a House labor\nsubcommittee today the American\nFederation of Labor would support a\nminimum wage of 30 cents an hour\nif mandatory annual increases were\nprovided.\nMr. Green discussed wage-hour leg\nislation with the subcommittee for\nmore than an hour at an informal\nmeeting arranged by Representative\nWelch, Republican, of California.\nHe said he told the group that while\nthe federation regarded 40 cents an\nhour as a fair minimum wage, it\nwould be willing to support a lower\nfigure in order to otbain passage of\nlabor standard legislation.\nHe insisted, however, that the lower\nfigure be a universal minimum below\nwhich no employer engaged in inter\nstate commerce could go.\nMr. Green said he suggested the\n\u201cceiling\" for hours be established at\n40 hours a week, asserting that was\nbased on present economic conditions.\nKANSAS CITY P.W. A.\nPROBE IS ORDERED\nWilliams Aide Will Investigate\nCharge of Political Activity\non Part of Workers.\nBy the Associated Press.\nAubrey Williams, acting W. P. A.\nadministrator, ordered an investiga\ntion today of charges of political ac\ntivity on the part.of relief workers\nin Kansas City, Mo.\nHe said Howard O. Hunter, assist\nant administrator of the Midwestern\nregion, would proceed to Kansas City\nwithin a few days.\nMr. Williams asserted that while\nhe had no affidavits showing dismissal\nof any W. P. a. worker because of\npolitical affiliation, he had ordered\nan investigation \"in line with the\nW. P. a. policy of guarding against\ninfringement of its regulations which\nban such activities.\u201d\nOne foreman and a timekeeper. Mr.\nWilliams said, had been accused of\nintimating to workers that they might\nsuffer political reprisals.\nThere was no evidence, however,\nthat such a threat had been carried\nout, he continued.\nMount Asama in Eruption.\nKARUIZAWA, Japan. March 25\n\u2014Mount Asama. inactive exactly one\nyear, erupted without warning today.\nSmall rocks pelted Karuizawa, the\nnearest town, a resort center 85 miles\nnorthwest of Tokio. No casualties\nwere reported.\nENGLAND\u2019S LABOR\nCALLS ON LEAGUE\nTO ACT FOR PEACE\nLeaders Score Chamberlain\nStatement of Foreign\nPolicy Yesterday.\nCENTRAL EUROPE, SPAIN\nAPPEASEMENT IS URGED\nDemands Inject New Factor Into\nArms Construction to\nBacking Warning.\nBy the Associated Pres*.\nLONDON. March 25.\u2014Leaders of\nBritish labor today assailed Prime\nMinister Chamberlain's declaration of\nforeign policy and called for an im\nmediate meeting of the Assembly of the\nLeague of Nations to ronsider \"the\nappeasement of Europe.\u201d\nMen representing the Trades Union\nCongress and the Labor party, in\ncluding labor members of Parliament,\ntook the action at an emergency joint\nmeeting.\nThis was a direct outcome of the\nPrime Minister's historic statement\nin the House of Commons yesterday\nand of his interview with labor lead\ners Wednesday, when he sought their\nsupport of plans to speed up rearma\nment.\nAppeasement Steps Sought.\nThe leaders of labor demanded\n\"special consideration by European\nmembers of the League, particularly\nFrance, Great Britain and Russia,\nof steps to be taken to bring appease\nment to.Central Europe and Spain.\u201d\nLabor's demands injected a new\nfactor into Mr. Chamberlain's efforts\nto back his policies by the arms pro\ngram he already has warned the na\ntion must cost more than the $7,\n500.000,000 originally intended for it.\nMr. Chamberlain yesterday warned\nBritain she might have to fight, even\nthough in his long-awaited pro\nnouncement of policy in Central Eur\nope he refused to bind the nation in\nadvance to a plfdge to halt any Ger\nman aggression in that quarter.\nwhere peace and war are\nconcerned legal obligations are not\nalone involved, and if war were to\nbreak out it would be unlikely to be\nconfined to those who have assumed\nsuch obligations,\u201d he declared.\nPicturing rearmed Britain as a sen\ntinel of world peace, Mr. Chamberlain\nsaid all else was secondary to imme\ndiate rearmament on a war-time\nscale.\nArms Hinge Upon labor.\nLabor leaders wbto- placed in the\nforefront of the revived effort to weigh\nMr. Chamberlain's words with guns\nand planes.\nThe government's appeal to labor\nrecalled a similar plan in March,\n1915, to increase production of World\nWar munitions, when the government\nproposed there should be no strikes\nor lockouts, proposed referring of dis\nputes to arbitration and sought sus\npension of restrictions tending to\nlimit production or employment of\nsemi-skilled and female labor.\nAs a result of the government's ap\npeal then the workers prepared their\nown plan, which speedily was modi\nfied and adopted.\nSpeech Generally Welcomed.\nThe British press generally wel\ncomed the prime minister\u2019s declara\ntion of policy, although there was\nsome criticism of lack of a more posi\ntive statement.\nTo those who felt Mr. Chamber\nlain\u2019s policy somewhat obscure, favor\nable commentators answered that the\nprime minister's strategy was like that\nof a quarterback in a football game\nwho calls the plays when he sees\nhow the opposition\u2019s attack is de\nveloping.\nOther members of Mr. Chamber\nlain\u2019s team, they said, were France,\nBelgium, Portugal, Egypt, Iraq,\nCanada. South Africa, New Zealand,\nAustralia and the remainder of the\nempire.\nThe prime minister was now wait\ning, they said, to see which way the\nball w'as going.\nObligations Cited.\nIn his speech, Mr. Chamberlain\nsaid Britain had obligations which\nmight lead to use of her arms with\nFrance, Belgium, Portugal, Iraq and\nEgypt, besides the responsibilities of\ndefense of her own empire.\nClement R. Attlee, leader of the\nofficial opposition in Commons,\ncharged the government with a policy\nconnivance at insurgent victory in\nSpain.\nSummary of Today's Star\nPage. Page.\nAmusements B-20 Obituary_A-10\nComics-B-8-9 Radio. C-4\nEditorials-A-8 Short Story.. B-8\nEditorials_A-8 society. B-3\nFinance_ A-I3 Sports_C-l-3\nLost Found. C-4 Woman\u2019s Pg. B-19\nFOREIGN.\nJapan prepares big oil contract for\nMexico. Page A-l\nEngland's labor calls on League to act\nfor peace. Page A-1\nGerman-trained Chinese bulwark\nChinese defenses. Page A-3\nCatholic leaders in Austria support\nGerman union. Page A-4\nRebels menacing strategic Aragon\nstronghold. Page A-6\nNATIONAL.\nReorganization measure faces new at\ntack on Monday. Page A-l\nAll Senate groups agree on form of\nT. V. A. resolution. Page A-l\nEstate and gift tax changes rejected\nby Senators. Page A-l\nWASHINGTON AND VICINITY.\nCongress probe of group health con\ntroversy to be asked. Page A-l\nCourt asked to probe McLean commit\nment to sanitarium. Page A-2\nFirst showing of new court building\nslated today. Page B-l\nSPORTS.\nChase's fine work marks hing| as slab\nstarter for Nats. Pige C-l\nSt. John\u2019s playing champs in title\nbasket tourney. Page C-l\nBees are sure their antique hurlers\nwill be winners. Page C-2\nEastern, with many vets, is choice in\nschool base ball. Page C-3\nEDITORIAL AND COMMENT.\nEditorials. Page A-8\nThis and That. Page A-8\nWashington Observations. Page A-8\nPolitical Mill. Page A-8\nAnswers to Questions. Page A-8\nThe Capital Parade. Page A-9\nDavid Lawrence. Page A-9\nDorothy Thompson. Page A-9\nConstantine Brown. Page A-9\nLemuel Parton. Page A-9\nFINANCIAL.\nCorporate bonds ease (table). Page A-13\nRetail trade climbs. Page A-13\nFreight loadings down. Page A-13\nCapital transit loss smaller. Page A-14\nStocks slump again (table). Page A-14\nCurb shares mixed (table). PageA-15\n\nMISCELLANY.\nShipping News. Page B-l#\nCity News in Brief. Page B-19\nNature\u2019s Children. Page B-18\nService Orders. Page B-18\nVital Statistics. Page C-4\nBedtime Story. Page C-8\nLetter-Out. Page C-8\nCrossword Puzzle. t i|Page C-8\nContract Bridge. B^Page C-9\nCONGRESSMEN-* 10,000\u00b0\nCOMtsslWM. SECRETARIES'} 20000(11\n1. K. \u201el(,\n\nf i don't\n(SEE MY\n3 NAME IN\nt LIST'\nREORGANIZING BIEL\nFACES NEW MOVE\nSenator King Will Seek to\nStrike Out Proposed\nWelfare Unit.\nBACKGROUND\u2014\nShake-up in Government de\npartmental structure with abolish\nment of some agencies and merger\nof others is one of administration's\nviost prized reform proposals. In\nface of bitter opposition, bill was\nwithheld from special session last\nfall, but majority leadership is at\ntempting to gain enactment this\nspring.\nBy J. A. O\u2019LEARY.\nThe controversial Government reor\nganization bill laces attack on a new\nflank Monday, when Senator King,\nDemocrat, of Utah will seek to strike\nout the proposed Department of Wel\nfare.\nHe announced this Intention late\nyesterday, just, before the Senate\nagreed to vote at 3 p.m. Monday on\nthe Walsh motion to send the entire\nmeasure back to -immiltM amfif\nthat fails, to vote on final passage \u00bbf\nthe bill at 5 p.m. that day.\nThe agreement that, will bring to\nan end a month of bitter controversy\nover reorganization powers being dele\ngated to the President, was adopted\nonly after steps had been taken to\npreclude any last-minute effort to\nattach the anti-lynching bill to the\npending measure.\nAfter opponents of the reorganiza\ntion program had failed yesterday in\ntheir last major fight, to prevent abo\nlition of the General Accounting Office,\nSenator Walsh, Democrat, of Massa\nchusetts paved the way for the final\nshowdown by moving to recommit\nthe bill for further study.\nBreach in Ranks.\nThe vote on this motion will prove\nthe climax of the long parliamentary\nstruggle, marked by the sharpest\nbreach in Democratic ranks since\nthe Supreme Court enlargement plan\nof last year.\nWhile the agreement to vote Mon\nday cleared the legislative path for\nother measures in the meantime, the\nverbal battle will be renewed for sev\neral hours Monday before the decisive\nroll call is taken.\nIndications last night were the mo\ntion to recommit would be decided by\na margin of four or five votes. Both\nsides are expected to strive for their\nmaximum strength on the motion to\nrecommit.\nAmendment Reports.\nThere had been reports at the Capi\ntol early yesterday that the anti\nlynching bill, against which Southern\nSenators staged a successful filibuster\nin January, might be brought forth\nas an amendment by some opponent\nof the reorganization bill.\nWhen Majority Leader Barkley pre\nsented the request for an agreement\non a time to vote Monday, Senator\nGeorge, Democrat, of Georgia an\nnounced he would object to any unan\nimous consent proposal unless it ex\ncluded from time limitation any mo\ntion that might be offered on the\nanti-lynching subject.\nWhen Senator Barkley tried to re\nphrase the agreement to exclude anti\nlynching from the time limit if it\nshould be brought up, Senator Clark,\nDemocrat, of Missouri, a leading op\nponent of the reorganization bill, in\nquired:\nClears Up Situation.\n\u201cInasmuch as the whole bill is in\nthe nature of a lynching bill, would\nnot the request of the Senator from\nKentucky amount to obviating a vote\non the bill itself?\u201d\nA few minutes later, however. Sena\ntor Clark cleared up the situation by\nassuring Senator George he had no\nintention of offering the anti-lynch\ning bill to the reorganization measure,\nalthough reserving the right to offer\nit to some later bill.\nThe Senate then adopted a separate\nagreement under which it will not be\nin order to bring up the anti-lynching\nproblem before reorganization is dis\nposed of. With this agreement, no\nfurther objection was made to voting\nMonday on reorganization.\nFunctions Restricted.\nSenator Bulkley, Democrat, of\nOhio took the lead yesterday in hav\ning supporters of the bill adopt a\nseries of amendments to restrict the\nfunctions of the Resources Planning\nBoard, which becomes a permanent\nagency under this bill.\nSenator King said he would seek\nto prevent establishment of the new\nWelfare Department on the ground\nits proposed functions Jalready are\nbeing performed by exiting agencies,\nHitler to Make\n14 Speeches on\nUnion Election\nAddress Campaign to\nStart Tonight in\nEast Prussia.\nBy ih# Associated Press.\nBERLIN, March 25.\u2014Reichsfuehrer\nHitler flew today to Koenigsberg, East\nPrussia, where tonight he will start\na series of 14 speeches in the cam\npaign for the April 10 plebiscite on\nabsorption of Austria.\nThe Peuhrer's schedule called for\nappearances in several Austrian towns.\nIt will end with an address at Vienna\nthe day before the vote.\nMaking his first visit to Koenigs\nberg in two years. Hitler w'as received\nwith the usual ovation. He arrived\nby plane at 5 p.m.\nIn the German polling April 10 on\nAustrian union with Germany. -Ja\u201d\n<yes> voters will have a circle the size\nof a half dollar in which to mark their\n\"X.\u201d while \"Nein\u201d (not voters must\nmake the cross in a circle only as\nlarge as a dime.\nThe official Reichs Gesetzblatt to\nday disclosed the form of the ballot\nfor the plebiscite and for greater Ger\nmany's Reichstag election.\nThe question reads: \"Are you in\nagreement with the reunion of Au\nstria with the German Reich accom\nplished March 13. 1938. and do you\nvote for the list of our Fuehrer, Adolf\nHitler\u201d\nGRAY IS INDICTED\nON SECOND CHARGE\nFormer Montgomery Building\nInspector Is Accused of\nEmbezzlement of $710.\nB.v e Staff Correspondent of The Star.\nROCKVILLE, Md., March 25.\u2014-All\nIndictment charging embezzlement of\ni $710 of county funds was returned\nj by the Montgomery County grand\njurv today against E. J. Gray, former\ncounty building inspector. The in\ndictment. according to State's Attorney\nI James H. Pugh, covered alleged mis\nappropriation of funds in connection\nwith the issuance of oil burner per\nmits during the entire term Gray\nheld office.\nRefusing to accept Gray\u2019s tendered\nresignation last fall, the Board of\nCounty Commissioners subsequently\ndismissed him after the grand jury at\nthat time returned an indictment\ncharging an embezzlement by Gray\nof $244 in connection with the issuanae\nof oil burner permits. Gray is at\nliberty on $1,500 bond, as a result of\nthe former indictment.\nIt is expected that the grand jury\nwill have completed investigating ap\nproximately 135 cases not later than\nTuesday. About 26 indictments, chiefly\nfor petty offenses such as assault,\nrobbery and larceny have been re\nturned to date.\nOLD YACHT MAYFLOWER\nWILL BE SOLD FOR DEBT\nFormer Presidential Vessel to Go\non Block to Satisfy Iron\nWorks Claims.\nBy l he Associated Press.\nNORFOLK, Va\u201e March 25\u2014The\nformer presidential yacht Mayflower,\nor what is left of her, is to be sold for\ndebt at Wilmington, N. C., at noon\nMonday, it was learned here today.\nDuring the administration of Pres\nident Hoover the Mayflower was\nabandoned as a presidential craft and\nwas 'decommissioned at the Philadel\nphia Navy Yard. She caught Are\nwhile moored at a wharf there and\nburned to the water\u2019s edge. Her hull\nwas sold once to parties who planned\nto consign it to the junk heap.\nThen it was resold and the new\nbuyers decided to convert her into a\nfloating dance salon and tow her to\nWashington to remain there.\nThe work of fitting her out for her\nproposed career as a pleasure palace\nwas started at Wilmington, but was\nnever completed. She is to be sold to\nsatisfy claims filed, by a Wilmington\niron works.\nArabs Blow TJp Military Car.\nJERUSALEM, March 25 (IP).\u2014Arab\nsaboteurs today blew up a military\ncar patroling the railway line near\nGaza, killing on^Sritlsh soldier and\nwounding anothedP*\nROW OVER G. H. A.\nScott Resolution Asking Quiz\nWill Be Introduced\non Monday.\nBACKGROUND\u2014\nGroup Health Association, Inc.,\n1328 I street, is charged with cor\nporate practice of medicine by Dis\ntrict Medical Society, which has\nousted one G. H. A. doctor; pre\nvents its society members from per-\nsonal consultations with G. H. A.\ndoctors. Operation on young wom\nan G. H. A. member has stirred\ncontroversy.\nA resolution for a congressional in\nvestigation of the increasingly bitter\nrow between the Group Health Asso\nciation and the Medical Society will\nbe introduced Monday in the House.\nRepresentative Byron N. Scott, Dem\nocrat, of California, whose champion\nship of G. H. A. and attack on the\nMedical Society had provoked the\nsociety to charge him with \u201cslander,\"\nannounced he would ask the House\nMonday to authorize an investigation\nby a selected committee.\nRepresentative Paul W. Shafer, Re\npublican. of Michigan, said he would\nseek an investigation of the contro\nversy by the Hospitals and Charities\nSubcommittee of the House District\nCommittee, of which he is a member.\nSees Action Unnecessary.\nMr. Shafer believes an authorization\nbv the House is unnecessary and that\nan investigation can be initiated at\nany time by the hospitals and charities\nsubcommittee.\nRepresentative Jenckes, Democrat,\nof Indiana is chairman of the sub\ncommittee. Mr. Shafer said as soon as\nshe returns to Washington from a trip\nto Indiana he proposes to urge her to\norder the investigation.\n\"If the charges Mr. Scott made in\nthe House are true.\u201d declared Mr.\nShafer. \u201cI believe it is the duty of\nour subcommittee to make an im\nmediate investigation.\nSerious Charge, He Says.\n\u201cI cannot believe a Washington\ndoctor would refuse to operate on a\npatient, as Mr. Scott has charged, be\ncause she happened to be a member of\nG. H. A. That's a serious charge, and\nif it's true, something should be done\nto correct the situation. And our\nsubcommittee is the proper place to\nstart.\n\"Inasmuch a.s the charges have been\nmade, Mr. Scott should be called before\nthe subcommittee to prove them. But\nI think the inquiry will disprove the\ncharges.\"\nCrux of the latest bitterness in the\nfight is a young woman member of\nGroup Health Association. An opera\ntion she underwent in a hospital here\ndrew serious charges from Representa\ntive Scott and G. H. A., and sharp\ndenials and counter-charges from the\nMedical Society.\nSays Operation Refused.\nG. H. A. and Representative Scott\ncharged the woman had been refused\nthe privilege of an emergency opera\ntion for appendicitis by a G. H. A.\nsurgeon at one hospital and that later,\nwhen operated on by another surgeon\nat another hospital, she was found to\nhave a ruptured appendix.\nDr. P. X. McGovern, public rela\ntions chairman for the Medical So\nciety, charged Representative Scott\nwith \u201cslander\u201d and with making state\nments \u201cgrossly untrue.\u201d He said the\nfacts showed the young woman's ap\npendix was not ruptured nor acute.\nDecision to introduce the investi\ngation resolution Monday was an\nnounced by Representative Scott to\nday, following the attack on him by\nDr. McGovern last night.\nFirst Saw Letter.\nExplaining he had read a letter\nfrom Dr. McGovern, in which the\nmedical society spokesman had de\nmanded a retraction by yesterday\nafternoon. Mr. Scott said:\n\u201cThe letter was written March 23\nand arrived in my office on March 24,\nwhile I was in New York. I just re\nturned from New York last night and\nthis morning I had the first oppor\ntunity to read the letter which he had\nreleased to the press.\n\u201cHe says in his letter that I had\nmade the questioned statement with\nout full knowledge of the facts, or\nthat some one misrepresented the\nfacts to me.\n\u201cI made the statement,\u201d continued\nMr. Scott,\u201d on what were purported\nto be facts presented to me by officers\nof the Group eHalth Association. They\nsay the statement was true. Dr. Me\n(Set C. WA., Page A-4.)\nESTATE AND GIFT\nTAX CHANGES BY\nHOUSEREJECTED\nSenators Restore Provisions\nof Present Law, Granting\nStates 25 Pet Cent.\nGOV. LEHMAN\u2019S CRITICISM\nINFLUENCES COMMITTEE\nProposal to Relieve Insolvent\nBanks of Income Levies\nIs Accepted.\nBACKGROUND\u2014\nSteady barrage of criticism, and\ncomplaint by business led adminis\ntration to point of being willing to\nmodify its favored theories of tax\ning undistributed corporate profits\nand treating capital gains and\nlosses for tax purposes. Relief given\nin House bill, however, did not go to\npoint of abandoning the adminis\ntration ideas as docs Senate com\nmittee action.\nBy JOHN C. HENRY.\nThe Senate Finance Committee to\nday rejected House changes in estate\nand gift taxes and restored provisions\nof the present law to the pending tax\nmodification measure.\nIn effect, the Senate decision re\ntains for the States an average credit\nof 25 per cent on death duties pay\nable to the Federal Government in\nstead of 16 'i per cent proposed by the\nHouse.\nThe action was taken in the wake\nof sweeping criticism by Gov. Herbert\nH. Lehman of New York and other\nState officials of proposed changes in\nFederal death taxes by whieh further\nrevenue from this source would be di\nverted from the State treasuries to\nthe Federal Treasury.\nAs Chairman Harrison announced\nihe Finance Committee action today\nhe also released estimates from the\nTreasury Department that the com\nmittee decision of yesterday afternoon\non treatment of capital gams and\nlosses would mean an extra $3,200,000\nin revenue for t\u00a3e calendar year\n1938. The House program for such\ngains and losses was calculated to\nraise $42,200,000 this year w;hile the\nSenate program of yesterday is esti\nmated at $45,400,000.\nTo Relieve Insolvent Banks.\nThe committee also decided today to\naccept a proposal of Senator Brown,\nDemocrat, of Michigan, to relieve in\nsolvent banks of Federal income taxes\nduring the period of their insolvency.\nIf it is found that the institutions are\nable to pay 100 cents on each dollar of\nobligations, however, the income levy\ncould then be applied.\nA second amending proposal ap\nproved was offered by Senator Clark,\nDemocrat, of Missouri to permit cor\nporations to continue liquidation of\nsubsidiary companies under rules es\ntablished in 1935 if such liquidation\nhad been started under those rules.\nThe rules were changed in 1936. Only\nabout five corporations would be af\nfected by today's relief, it was said.\nWith regard to the estate tax\nchanges, the modifications included in\nthe House bill were calculated to sim\nplify the present complex structure.\nAcknowledging this meritorious theory.\nChairman Harrison pointed out today\nihat the House proposal not only\nwould affect the revenues which States\nfairly expect from their death taxes,\nbut would force a number of States\nto change their own laws and would\nbe an added item of controversy in\nseeking speedy Senate enactment of\nthe pending bill. He admitted that\nthe criticism of Gov. Lehman had\nhad great influence on the committee.\nComputed Under Two Lawn.\nUnder the present system. Federal\nestate taxes are computed under two\ndifferent Jaws, one of 1926 and one of\nIn brief, the 1926 statute allows ex\nemption of $100,000 and graduates\nrates up to 20 per cent. The 1933 law\nallows $40,000 exemption and runs the\nrates up to 70 per cent.\nIn practice, the taxpayers must first\ncompute a tentative tax under the\n1932 law. He then computes the lax\nunder the 1926 law and subtracts this\nfrom his tentative figure under the\n1932 formula. Th^ remainder is the\nFederal estate tax payable.\nIn the computation of the 1926 ta\ncredit is allowed up to 80 per cent of\nthe tax paid the State but no credit\nts given for State payments in the\n1932 schedule. In its operation, such\na structure gives estate taxpayers of\nthe State of New York, for example, an\nactual credit of about 25 per cent.\nUnder the House bill, the double\ncomputation now in effect would be\nabandoned by enactment of a single\nrate schedule and credit of 16'-j per\ncent would be allowed on account of\ndeath duties paid the States.\nIn the gift tax provisions, the House\nbill would have cut the exemption from\nper donee per year $5,000 to $3,000.\nThe Senate Committee festered the\nexemption to its present $5,000 level.\nNo roll call votes were taken this\nmorning.\nRally Strength tor Plan.\nEncouraged by the ease with which\nthey rallied an overwhelming major\nity of their committee colleagues yes\nterday to support major tax modifica\ntions in a direction calculated to en\ncourage a business revival, leaders of\nthe committee were combining the\ntask of further revisions in committee\nwith that of lining up strength to\nmaintain their position when the bill\nreaches the floor.\nAround the nucleus of 17 Democrats\nand Republicans who approved yes\nterday\u2019s most significant decision, that\nof eliminating the principle of taxing\nundistributed profits of corporations,\nthere appeared almost certain support\nfrom about 22 other Senate members.\nWith Majority Leader Barkley of Ken\ntucky expected to hold some 40 others\nin line in favor of restoring the ad\nministration's own tax theories, there\nremains a group of nearly 20 whose\nposition is undetermined.\nThe ultimate decision of a dozen of\nthis borderline group will decide the\n(See TprcsrPaeTAW.7)","height":"31080","width":"22192"}}
